    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Scirpus fimbriatus are flavonoids and phenolic acids, specifically isorhapontigenin, quercetin, and ferulic acid, which possess antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties. Isorhapontigenin has been shown to exhibit significant antioxidant and anti-inflammatory activity by scavenging free radicals and inhibiting pro-inflammatory enzymes. Quercetin has been found to have anti-inflammatory and antiviral properties, while ferulic acid has been reported to have antioxidant and anti-inflammatory effects. Additionally, Scirpus fimbriatus contains essential oils, including beta-pinene, limonene, and bornyl acetate, which may contribute to its antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory activities. These bioactive compounds likely contribute to the plant's traditional uses, including the treatment of fever, cough, and respiratory infections.",
